<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06342181 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06342181 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  IRAQ; DEATH; MURDER; MIDEAST; VIOLENCE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Across northern Iraq, Kurds, free now from Iraqi President Saddam Hussein'sgrip, have been finding mass graves, torture chambers, elaborate prisonsystems and documents from secret police files that attest to the innerworkings of one of the region's harshest dictatorships.;   In the city ofSulaimaniya, local officials say they have unearthed more than 200 bodies inthe last two months, and new sites to be excavated are being discovered everyweek.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  KURDS OFFER PROOF OF KILLINGSMASS GRAVES BACK CLAIMS OF CRUELTY  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Kurds have long charged Saddam's government with human rights abuses.;  Some especially severe cases have been independently substantiated and widelypublicized, including attacks with chemical weapons on Kurdish villagers atHalabja during the war between Iran and Iraq.;   Obvious repression; But thegraves and other recent discoveries offer evidence of the wide extent ofBaghdad's repression. They are coming to light now that the Kurds have beenleft to run their affairs and rebuild their lives in the aftermath of theAmerican-led military effort to protect them from Saddam's forces.;   Baghdadcrushed a Kurdish uprising after its defeat in the Persian Gulf war, forcinghundreds of thousands of Kurds to flee for months into Iran and Turkey.;  &quot;When we first complained about these human rights violations, the world didnot listen,&quot; said Jalal Talabani, one of two top Kurdish guerrilla leaders.;  &quot;Now that we come forward with the evidence, this information is harder toignore.&quot;;   Indiscriminate killing charged; Kurdish leaders contend that morethan 180,000 people have disappeared in the last decade at the hands of theIraqi secret police.;   They say the Iraqis killed anyone, including youngchildren, who they believe supported the outlawed Kurdish guerrilla movementor who belonged to a family that had ties with Kurdish rebels.;   Whenconfronted in the past with charges of abusing Kurds, Iraqi officials have ingeneral denied wrongdoing, saying actions in the region had been taken againstinfiltrators from Iran or against traitors.;   Iraqi officials have alsopointed to at least one mass killing by Kurdish guerrillas in October, when 60Iraqi soldiers who surrendered during skirmishes in the Sulaimaniya area wereslain by their Kurdish captors, according to the account of a Reutersreporter.;   Kurdish leaders promised to investigate the killings and bringthose guilty to justice, but the investigation has yet to produce results.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  New York Times  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Sulaimaniya, Iraq  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911207  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  December  </MONTH><PG.COL>  17A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  378  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Saturday, December 7, 199100342181,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>